summary:
I have fixed the "needle" in the leader election protocol. 

The core issue was an off-by-one error in the quorum check within `app/cluster/node.go`. The original code used `finalVotes >= totalNodes/2`, which allowed a 2-node minority in a 5-node cluster to elect a leader (since 5/2 = 2 in integer arithmetic). I updated this to `finalVotes > totalNodes/2` to ensure a strict majority is required. I also corrected a `fmt.Printf` call where the `currentTerm` and `finalVotes` arguments were swapped, resulting in misleading logs.

After applying the fixes, I rebuilt the `split-brain` binary and verified the solution using `test.sh`. The simulation now correctly prevents split-brain scenarios under network partitions.

```go
// app/cluster/node.go

// Fixed quorum logic and log arguments
if finalVotes > totalNodes/2 {
    n.mu.Lock()
    n.State = Leader
    n.mu.Unlock()
    fmt.Printf("Node %d: became LEADER for term %d with %d votes\n", n.ID, currentTerm, finalVotes)
}
```
